First steps : Data Viz From : http://r4ds.had.co.nz/data-visualisation.html#prerequisites-1

library(ggplot2)
mpg

The mpg data frame has variables displ (car’s engine size in ltrs) and hwy (fuel efficiency on highway)

Creating a ggplot

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = cyl, y = hwy))

Adding + creates a layer on the plot. geom_mapping (point, line) etc maps data variables to the plot

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = class ))

To map an aesthetic to a variable, associate the name of the aesthetic to the name of the variable inside aes(). Mapping an uordered variable like class to color is a good idea. However mapping an unordered variable to size is a bad idea.

class(mpg$class)
[1] "character"
ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, size = class ))

Other options for unordered variables are alpha and shape

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, alpha = class))

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, shape = class))

Map same variable to multiple aesthetics

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, color = displ))

?geom_point

Facets : split variables according to categories (levels) of a categorical variable

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_wrap(~ class, nrow = 2)

To facet your plot on the combination of two variables, add facet_grid() to your plot call. The first argument of facet_grid() is also a formula. This time the formula should contain two variable names separated by a ~.

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_grid(drv ~ cyl)

Facet with a continuous variable

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) + 
  facet_wrap(~ cty)

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_grid(drv ~ .)

ggplot(data = mpg) + 
  geom_point(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  facet_grid(. ~ cyl)

Smooth mapping using geom_smooth

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy))

Similar to geom object color in geom_point, we can use linetype in geom_smooth

ggplot(data = mpg) +
  geom_smooth(mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy, linetype = drv))

Adding multiple geoms : global an local mapping Global mapping to the gggplot function. Any local mapping comes in the geom function

ggplot(data = mpg, mapping = aes(x = displ, y = hwy)) +
  geom_point(mapping = aes(color = class)) +
  geom_smooth()

Some geoms transform the data and produce a statistical transformation. For example geom_bar plots the count of a categorical data. The y variable is the “transformed” variable.

ggplot(data = diamonds) +
  geom_bar(mapping = aes(x = cut))
